        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-01-11 05:21:13.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 11:\n\nYury, could you please take a look and share whether similar solution to what you done in portal-vnc can be applied in this case.",
        "patchset_number": 11
      },
      {
        "id": "0f71ece0a6ac687acbe2a6745cf37145eff47ccf",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 345,
          "name": "Yury Novitsky",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "yury.novitsky@amdocs.com",
          "username": "yuryn"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-01-11 08:15:41.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 11:\n\n> Yury, could you please take a look and share whether similar\n > solution to what you done in portal-vnc can be applied in this\n > case.\n\nYes, it can be used.\nI understand that currently there is no \"ideal\" solution on k8s for the hostname to hostname mapping - on the one hand additions to /etc/hosts can be overwritten by k8s, on the other hand the officially-provided solution allows hostname to IP mapping only, which leads to the problems that this fixed IP: \n1. Should be in the k8s cluster IP range;\n2. Should not be already occupied by other (non-ONAP) service.\n\nI do think that periodical refresh of the /etc/hosts file is better in this case as it:\n1. Does not require fixed cluster IP for a service;\n2. Does not require redeployment of the \"client\" components if the \"server\" component IP changed (e.g. in the fixed cluster IP solution - must change the IP)",
        "patchset_number": 11
      },
